 conduct to her household management. The book also includes Gournay's last revisions (1641) of her two best-known feminist treatises, The Equality of Men and Women and The Ladies' Complaint. The editors provide a general overview of Gournay's career, as well as individual introductions and extensive annotations for each work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aWomen editorszFrancexHistoryy16th centuryvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  awomen, womens, issues, studies, feminism, feminist, gender, sexuality, identity, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, humanities, english major, college, university, literature, literary, writer, france, french, europe, european, western, translation, psychological, psychology, novel, autobiographical, sexual, morals, household, roles, rights, equality.1 aHillman, Richard.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuesnel, Colette.1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022630555440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226305264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226305264/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles